You are correct in that this is not the *React way* of doing it. There is no need to &quot;hide&quot; the element as is usually done in vanilla JS or jQuery, React will handle that based on the `state` or props that contain information about which pieces are on the board.

You need to send an identifier to the piece in order to have a callback for the Parent component to update the state based on the pieces:

```javascript
// constructor:

this.state = {
  pieces: [&quot;pawn&quot;, &quot;rook&quot;, &quot;queen&quot;]
};


// render:

{ this.state.pieces.map((piece, i) =&gt; (
  &lt;Piece type={piece} onClick={() =&gt; this.deletePiece(i)} /&gt;
}
```

[Here&#39;s a codesandbox of a working example.][1]

(**Note:** Ideally pieces would have an ID instead of just an index to avoid re-renders, but the important part of the example is to see how the variable `i` allows the callback to delete the piece back in the parent component) 

  [1]: https://codesandbox.io/embed/thirsty-jackson-wh6kz

